abetes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic neuropathy","Hereditary neuropathy","Peroneal neuropathy","Radial neuropathy","Ulnar neuropathy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms described are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E, which often presents with weakness and atrophy of the hand muscles, particularly the intrinsic muscles. The intermittent numbness and tingling associated with elbow flexion suggest compression or irritation of the ulnar nerve at the elbow, commonly known as cubital tunnel syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeroneal neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E - Typically affects the lower limb, causing foot drop\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E - Often presents with a more widespread pattern of sensory and motor symptoms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E - Usually presents with a distal symmetric pattern affecting both sensory and motor nerves\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E - Typically causes wrist drop and affects the posterior aspect of the arm\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ulnar neuropathy often presents with weakness and atrophy of the hand muscles, particularly affecting the intrinsic muscles.","Symptoms of ulnar neuropathy can include intermittent numbness and tingling, especially when the elbow is flexed.","Ulnar neuropathy is commonly associated with compression or irritation of the ulnar nerve at the elbow, known as cubital tunnel syndrome."],"references":["Dy CJ, Mackinnon SE. Ulnar neuropathy: evaluation and management. Curr Rev Musculoskelet Med. 